---
import Layout from '@/layouts/Layout.astro';
import { Badge } from '@/components/ui/badge';

const updated = '2026-04-23';
---
<Layout
  title="Methodology — ConsentTheater"
  description="How ConsentTheater classifies cookies and domains by severity and category, what each label means, and where the data comes from."
>
  <section class="mx-auto w-full max-w-3xl px-6 pt-10 pb-12">
    <div class="mb-6">
      <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-muted-foreground">
        Methodology
      </p>
      <h1 class="mt-1 font-display text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight sm:text-3xl">
        How we classify trackers
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-2 text-[11px] text-muted-foreground">
        Last updated <time datetime={updated} class="font-mono">{updated}</time>
      </p>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
        Every entry in our catalogue carries a <strong>severity</strong> and a <strong>category</strong>.
        This page explains what those mean, how we assign them, and how to challenge a rating if you
        think it's wrong.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="space-y-10 text-sm leading-relaxed text-foreground/90">

      <section id="severity">
        <h2 class="mb-2 font-display text-lg font-bold tracking-tight">Severity</h2>
        <p>
          Severity is our short answer to the question: <em>how much does this tracker invade the
          visitor's privacy, and how much consent work does it create for the site operator under
          GDPR?</em> It is not a legal verdict — it is a quick, consistent signal.
        </p>

        <dl class="mt-5 space-y-5">
          <div id="critical" class="flex flex-col gap-2 sm:flex-row sm:items-start sm:gap-4">
            <dt class="sm:w-32 sm:shrink-0">
              <Badge variant="critical">critical</Badge>
            </dt>
            <dd class="text-sm">
              Cross-site tracking, ad targeting, fingerprinting, session recording, or any flow that
              builds a durable profile of the visitor across properties. Under GDPR these require
              <strong>explicit, prior, informed consent</strong>. Loading them before consent is
              usually non-compliant.
            </dd>
          </div>

          <div id="high" class="flex flex-col gap-2 sm:flex-row sm:items-start sm:gap-4">
            <dt class="sm:w-32 sm:shrink-0">
              <Badge variant="high">high</Badge>
            </dt>
            <dd class="text-sm">
              Persistent identifiers tied to personal data — cross-session analytics, CRM enrichment,
              marketing-automation cookies, social-login SDKs. Almost always
              <strong>consent-gated</strong>, though the personal-data footprint is smaller than
              critical.
            </dd>
          </div>

          <div id="medium" class="flex flex-col gap-2 sm:flex-row sm:items-start sm:gap-4">
            <dt class="sm:w-32 sm:shrink-0">
              <Badge variant="medium">medium</Badge>
            </dt>
            <dd class="text-sm">
              Aggregate or privacy-aware analytics, limited-scope conversion tracking, A/B testing
              without cross-site linkage. Typically consent-gated under GDPR, but with lower
              personal-data impact and often easier legitimate-interest arguments in context.
            </dd>
          </div>

          <div id="low" class="flex flex-col gap-2 sm:flex-row sm:items-start sm:gap-4">
            <dt class="sm:w-32 sm:shrink-0">
              <Badge variant="low">low</Badge>
            </dt>
            <dd class="text-sm">
              Functional and convenience — theme preference, language, CSRF tokens, shopping-cart
              state. Strictly necessary for the service the user asked for.
              <strong>Usually exempt from consent</strong> under GDPR Art. 5(3) ePrivacy "strictly
              necessary" carve-out, provided the scope stays genuinely functional.
            </dd>
          </div>
        </dl>
      </section>

      <section id="categories">
        <h2 class="mb-2 font-display text-lg font-bold tracking-tight">Categories</h2>
        <p>
          Category describes <em>what the tracker does</em>, not how invasive it is. A tracker in
          the <span class="font-mono">analytics</span> category can be low or critical depending on
          its design.
        </p>

        <dl class="mt-5 space-y-3">
          {[
            ['advertising', 'Ad-serving, ad personalisation, ad-click attribution, retargeting. Usually critical severity.'],
            ['analytics', 'Page-view and event measurement. Severity depends on whether identifiers cross sites and sessions.'],
            ['marketing', 'Email tracking, CRM enrichment, lead capture, sales intelligence. Personal-data heavy.'],
            ['social', 'Embedded share buttons, social logins, comment widgets. Frequently load third-party profile cookies even before interaction.'],
            ['session_recording', 'Records keystrokes, clicks, scroll behaviour, or full pixel-level session replay. Inherently high-risk under GDPR.'],
            ['fingerprinting', 'Canvas, WebGL, audio-context, font-enumeration, device-sensor fingerprinting — techniques that identify a browser without cookies.'],
            ['data_leak', "Transmits data (often email, phone, form-field values) to a third party in ways the user hasn't authorised. Frequently unintentional on the site operator's part."],
            ['tag_manager', 'Injects other scripts at runtime. Severity depends entirely on what ends up being loaded.'],
            ['consent', 'Consent-management platforms (CMPs) themselves. Reported so operators can verify their CMP is configured correctly.'],
            ['security', 'Bot detection, fraud prevention, CAPTCHA. Often necessary, but can carry significant personal-data fingerprinting as a side effect.'],
            ['functional', 'Language preference, UI state, shopping-cart session — things the site needs to work.']
          ].map(([name, desc]) => (
            <div class="flex flex-col gap-1 sm:flex-row sm:items-baseline sm:gap-4">
              <dt class="sm:w-44 sm:shrink-0">
                <code class="font-mono text-xs font-semibold">{name}</code>
              </dt>
              <dd class="text-sm text-foreground/90">{desc}</dd>
            </div>
          ))}
        </dl>
      </section>

      <section id="process">
        <h2 class="mb-2 font-display text-lg font-bold tracking-tight">How ratings are assigned</h2>
        <p>
          Each entry is reviewed against three questions:
        </p>
        <ol class="mt-3 list-decimal space-y-1 pl-6">
          <li>What does the vendor's own documentation say the tool is for?</li>
          <li>What does the tool actually do on the wire — cookies set, domains called, identifiers persisted?</li>
          <li>How does that map onto the GDPR consent requirement (Art. 6, 7, and the ePrivacy "strictly necessary" test)?</li>
        </ol>
        <p class="mt-3">
          Ratings are conservative: when in doubt, we rate <em>up</em>. A borderline high/critical
          entry will be marked critical until evidence shifts it.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="source">
        <h2 class="mb-2 font-display text-lg font-bold tracking-tight">Where the data lives</h2>
        <p>
          The full catalogue — every entry, its severity, its category, its description and
          documentation link — is maintained as an open-source package called the <em>Playbill</em>.
          It is distributed on npm as
          <a
            href="https://www.npmjs.com/package/@consenttheater/playbill"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener noreferrer"
            class="link font-mono"
          >@consenttheater/playbill</a>, and its source lives at
          <a
            href="https://github.com/ConsentTheater/playbill"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener noreferrer"
            class="link font-mono"
          >github.com/ConsentTheater/playbill</a>.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3">
          Every classification is traceable to a specific commit. If you disagree with a rating, you
          can open an issue or a pull request against that repository — include the vendor
          documentation or wire evidence that supports the correction, and we'll review.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="caveats">
        <h2 class="mb-2 font-display text-lg font-bold tracking-tight">Caveats</h2>
        <ul class="list-disc space-y-2 pl-6">
          <li>
            <strong>This is not legal advice.</strong> A GDPR compliance determination for a
            specific site depends on consent implementation, legal basis, data-subject rights, and
            the site's specific context. Consult a qualified DPO or lawyer.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>The catalogue is a snapshot.</strong> Vendors change their tools and cookies
            over time. We re-audit on a rolling basis, but any given entry may lag behind the
            vendor's current implementation.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Context changes severity.</strong> A cookie rated <Badge variant="medium">medium</Badge>
            in one context can become <Badge variant="critical">critical</Badge> if combined with
            other identifiers or loaded on a sensitive site (healthcare, minors). Use the rating as
            a starting point, not a verdict.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Unknown &ne; safe.</strong> A cookie or domain that returns "no match" on this
            site hasn't been audited by us — it is not a clean bill of health.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
